{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477425"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:01:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:01:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14525"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14525"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.11,0.51,0.07,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7220"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86165"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7220"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14525"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70433"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1293"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17534"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28603"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28771"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86165"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of bloody diarrhoea. He has had eight episodes of loose, bloody stools in the past 24 hours. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. His family recently visited a petting zoo and ate at a fast-food restaurant. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 130/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. He has dry mucous membranes and decreased skin turgor. His abdomen is soft but diffusely tender.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 115 g/L (110-140)\u003Cbr /\u003EWhite cell count: 8.5 x 10^9/L (5.0-15.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EPlatelet count: 280 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003Cbr /\u003EC-reactive protein: 15 mg/L (\u003C5)\u003Cbr /\u003EStool microscopy: Red blood cells present, minimal white blood cells\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely causative organism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Campylobacter jejuni","Salmonella enterica","Enterohemorrhagic Escherichia coli","Entamoeba histolytica","Shigella species"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with acute bloody diarrhoea after potential exposure through a petting zoo and fast food. The absence of significant fever and minimal white blood cells on stool microscopy, despite the presence of blood, is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003EEnterohemorrhagic Escherichia coli\u003C/strong\u003E (EHEC) infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEHEC, particularly O157:H7, is commonly associated with consumption of undercooked ground beef or exposure to contaminated food, water, or animals. The organism produces Shiga toxin, which directly damages the intestinal mucosa without triggering a significant inflammatory response, explaining the bloody diarrhoea without many white blood cells in the stool.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShigella species\u003C/strong\u003E typically cause a more inflammatory picture with high fever, elevated inflammatory markers, and numerous white blood cells in the stool, which are not present here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECampylobacter jejuni\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with high fever and inflammatory diarrhoea with white blood cells in the stool. The absence of significant inflammation makes this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESalmonella enterica\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes inflammatory diarrhoea with fever and elevated inflammatory markers. The lack of these features makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEntamoeba histolytica\u003C/strong\u003E causes amoebic dysentery, which typically has a more gradual onset and would show trophozoites on microscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of suspected EHEC infection involves careful fluid resuscitation and monitoring for complications such as hemolytic uremic syndrome. Antibiotics are generally contraindicated as they may increase the risk of hemolytic uremic syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Enterohemorrhagic Escherichia coli (EHEC) is a significant cause of bloody diarrhoea in children, particularly after consuming contaminated food or water.","EHEC infection typically presents with severe abdominal pain and bloody diarrhoea without fever.","The presence of bloody diarrhoea without significant fever or white blood cells in stool is characteristic of EHEC infection."],"references":["Hale TL, Keusch GT. Shigella. In: Baron S, editor. Medical Microbiology. 4th edition. Galveston (TX): University of Texas Medical Branch at Galveston; 1996. Chapter 22. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK8038/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70433"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14525"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70433"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-19T16:49:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-19T16:52:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"typ